{"title_page": "Xcaret", "text_new": "{{About|the Maya archaeological site|the modern-day commercial theme park and tourist attraction|Xcaret Park}}\n[[Image:Parque arqueol\u00f3gico xcaret.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n'''Xcaret''' ({{IPA-myn|\u0283ka\u02c8\u027eet}}) is a [[Maya civilization]] [[archaeological site]] located on the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]] coastline of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]], in the state of [[Quintana Roo]] in [[Mexico]]. The site was occupied by the [[pre-Columbian]] Maya and functioned as a port for navigation and an important [[Maya trade|Maya trading center]]. Some of the site's original structures are contained within a modern-day tourism development, the privately owned [[Xcaret Park]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rich|first=Grant J|title=Heritage or Heresy: Archaeology and Culture on the Maya Riviera by Cameron Jean Walker.|pages=182\u2013183|doi=10.1111/j.1548-1425.2010.01248_14.x|year=2010|journal=American Ethnologist|volume=37|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n==Toponomy==\n''Xcaret'' means \"small inlet\" in [[Mayan languages|Mayan]].<ref>The Mayan \"X\" is pronounced approximately \"Ish\", hence the name is similar to \"Ish Ka Ret\" when pronounced.</ref> Its name comes from its situation next to a small inlet that in the past served as a strategic location for navigation and commerce for the Maya. The original name of the site was ''p'ole''', from the root ''p'ol'' that means \"merchandise\" or \"deal of merchants\", which gives an idea of the economical relevance of the site. {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n==Site description==\n[[Image:Xcaret Mayan Ruins.jpg|thumb|Xcaret Mayan ruins.]]\n[[Image:Zona_arqueol\u00f3gica_xcaret.jpg|thumb|left|It is part of the remains that the park preserves.]]\n\nXcaret has many reserves that are open to the public. According to the research by the National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH)[http://www.inah.gob.mx/index.php], the first buildings of the site can be dated to 200 to 600 A.D., but the majority of them are from the period from 1200 to 1550 A.D. The constructions of the Late Post-Classical period are situated along the coast; some of them in strategic positions for surveillance. The site had a wall, but unlike the one in [[Tulum]] that was open towards the ocean, the wall at Xcaret defended the site from assaults coming from the sea. The wall may also have served to divide the solid ground of the interior from the swampy ground closer to the coast. {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nXcaret was inhabited at the time of the first stage of the Spanish incursion of [[Alonso D\u00e1vila]] and [[Francisco de Montejo]] into the eastern coast of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] (1527 to 1529). {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}} In 1548, [[Juan N\u00fa\u00f1ez Sede\u00f1o|Juan N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] was put in charge of Xcaret. At this time, a Spanish chapel was built. This implies that Xcaret remained an important settlement. The thatched roof of the chapel has disintegrated, but the walls remain standing. \nThe INAH divides the architectural formations into several different groups.\n\n== Historical significance ==\n[[File:Zona_Arqueologica_de_Xcaret_-_panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Zone Arqueologica of Xcaret]]\nThere are documents which suggest that Xcaret was one of the most active and economically significant Maya ports on the east coast. These documents make mention of marriages between the P'ole rulers and the people of [[Cozumel]]. These marriages were likely for political advances; they imply that Xcaret was politically important.<ref>{{cite web|last=National Institute of Anthropology and History|title=Zona Arqueol\u00f3gica Xcaret|url=http://www.inah.gob.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5488|accessdate=March 5, 2012|date=February 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Archaeological finds ==\nDuring archaeological explorations led by archaeologist Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9, 135 human remains were found in the chapel. In another case, DNA found on site was analyzed, and results showed that \"the distribution of mtDNA lineages in the Xcaret population contrasts sharply with that found in ancient Maya from [[Cop\u00e1n]], which lack lineages A and B. On the other hand, our results resemble more closely the frequencies of mtDNA lineages found in contemporary Maya from the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] and in other Native American contemporary populations of Mesoamerican origin.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Gonz\u00e1lez-Oliver, A., M\u00e1rquez-Morf\u00edn, L., Jim\u00e9nez, J. C. and Torre-Blanco, A. |doi=10.1002/ajpa.1118 | title=Founding Amerindian mitochondrial DNA lineages in ancient Maya from Xcaret, Quintana Roo | journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|date=2001|volume=116|issue=3|pages=230\u2013235 |pmid=11596002}}</ref> These findings suggest that the people of Xcaret are more closely related to contemporary Maya peoples than ancient peoples.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|20|34|41|N|87|07|09|W|display=title|region:MX-ROO_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n{{Maya sites}}\n{{Quintana Roo}}\n\n[[Category:Maya sites in Quintana Roo]]\n[[Category:Solidaridad (municipality)]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Quintana Roo]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Maya archaeological site|the modern-day commercial theme park and tourist attraction|Xcaret Park}}\n[[Image:Parque arqueol\u00f3gico xcaret.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n'''Xcaret''' ({{IPA-myn|\u0283ka\u02c8\u027eet}}) is a [[Maya civilization]] [[archaeological site]] located on the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]] coastline of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]], in the state of [[Quintana Roo]] in [[Mexico]]. The site was occupied by the [[pre-Colombian]] Maya and functioned as a port for navigation and an important [[Maya trade|Maya trading center]]. Some of the site's original structures are contained within a modern-day tourism development, the privately owned [[Xcaret Park]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rich|first=Grant J|title=Heritage or Heresy: Archaeology and Culture on the Maya Riviera by Cameron Jean Walker.|pages=182\u2013183|doi=10.1111/j.1548-1425.2010.01248_14.x|year=2010|journal=American Ethnologist|volume=37|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n==Toponomy==\n''Xcaret'' means \"small inlet\" in [[Mayan languages|Mayan]].<ref>The Mayan \"X\" is pronounced approximately \"Ish\", hence the name is similar to \"Ish Ka Ret\" when pronounced.</ref> Its name comes from its situation next to a small inlet that in the past served as a strategic location for navigation and commerce for the Maya. The original name of the site was ''p'ole''', from the root ''p'ol'' that means \"merchandise\" or \"deal of merchants\", which gives an idea of the economical relevance of the site. {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n==Site description==\n[[Image:Xcaret Mayan Ruins.jpg|thumb|Xcaret Mayan ruins.]]\n[[Image:Zona_arqueol\u00f3gica_xcaret.jpg|thumb|left|It is part of the remains that the park preserves.]]\n\nXcaret has many reserves that are open to the public. According to the research by the National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH)[http://www.inah.gob.mx/index.php], the first buildings of the site can be dated to 200 to 600 A.D., but the majority of them are from the period from 1200 to 1550 A.D. The constructions of the Late Post-Classical period are situated along the coast; some of them in strategic positions for surveillance. The site had a wall, but unlike the one in [[Tulum]] that was open towards the ocean, the wall at Xcaret defended the site from assaults coming from the sea. The wall may also have served to divide the solid ground of the interior from the swampy ground closer to the coast. {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nXcaret was inhabited at the time of the first stage of the Spanish incursion of [[Alonso D\u00e1vila]] and [[Francisco de Montejo]] into the eastern coast of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] (1527 to 1529). {{Citation needed|date=April 2016}} In 1548, [[Juan N\u00fa\u00f1ez Sede\u00f1o|Juan N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] was put in charge of Xcaret. At this time, a Spanish chapel was built. This implies that Xcaret remained an important settlement. The thatched roof of the chapel has disintegrated, but the walls remain standing. \nThe INAH divides the architectural formations into several different groups.\n\n== Historical significance ==\n[[File:Zona_Arqueologica_de_Xcaret_-_panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Zone Arqueologica of Xcaret]]\nThere are documents which suggest that Xcaret was one of the most active and economically significant Maya ports on the east coast. These documents make mention of marriages between the P'ole rulers and the people of [[Cozumel]]. These marriages were likely for political advances; they imply that Xcaret was politically important.<ref>{{cite web|last=National Institute of Anthropology and History|title=Zona Arqueol\u00f3gica Xcaret|url=http://www.inah.gob.mx/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5488|accessdate=March 5, 2012|date=February 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Archaeological finds ==\nDuring archaeological explorations led by archaeologist Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9, 135 human remains were found in the chapel. In another case, DNA found on site was analyzed, and results showed that \"the distribution of mtDNA lineages in the Xcaret population contrasts sharply with that found in ancient Maya from [[Cop\u00e1n]], which lack lineages A and B. On the other hand, our results resemble more closely the frequencies of mtDNA lineages found in contemporary Maya from the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] and in other Native American contemporary populations of Mesoamerican origin.\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Gonz\u00e1lez-Oliver, A., M\u00e1rquez-Morf\u00edn, L., Jim\u00e9nez, J. C. and Torre-Blanco, A. |doi=10.1002/ajpa.1118 | title=Founding Amerindian mitochondrial DNA lineages in ancient Maya from Xcaret, Quintana Roo | journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|date=2001|volume=116|issue=3|pages=230\u2013235 |pmid=11596002}}</ref> These findings suggest that the people of Xcaret are more closely related to contemporary Maya peoples than ancient peoples.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|20|34|41|N|87|07|09|W|display=title|region:MX-ROO_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n{{Maya sites}}\n{{Quintana Roo}}\n\n[[Category:Maya sites in Quintana Roo]]\n[[Category:Solidaridad (municipality)]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Quintana Roo]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: pre-Colombian \u2192 pre-Columbian as explained in the linked article.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xcaret"}
{"title_page": "Guy of Ibelin (died 1304)", "text_new": "{{For|others of this name|Guy of Ibelin (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Ibelin\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        = titular count of Jaffa and Ascalon\n| reign             = 1266 - 1304\n| predecessor       = [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John (jurist)]]\n| successor         = Philip (his son)\n| spouse            = Maria of Ibelin, Lady of Ascalon and Naumachia\n| issue             = Philip, Count of Jaffa<br>John<br>Maria, wife of [[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]<br>Hugh, Seneschal of Jerusalem<br>Balian\n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]-Jaffa\n| father            = [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John (jurist)]]\n| mother            = Maria of Barbaron\n| birth_date        = 1250/1255\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1304\n}}\n\n'''Guy of Ibelin''' (French: Guy d'Ibelin) (1250/1255 \u2013 1304), of the [[Ibelin family]], was [[County of Jaffa and Ascalon|Count of Jaffa and Ascalon]] during the latter part of the [[Crusades]].<ref>{{citation|first=W. H. |last=Rudt de Collenberg|title=Les Ibelin aux XIIIe et XIVe si\u00e8cles|journal=\u0395\u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u03af\u03c2 \u039a\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u0395\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd \u039a\u03cd\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5|volume= 9|year= 1977}}</ref><ref>{{citation|first=W. H. |last=R\u00fcdt de Collenberg|title=Familles de l'Orient latin XIIe-XIVe si\u00e8cles |publisher=Variorum reprints|year=1983|pages=117\u2013265}}, reprint of article ''Les Ibelin aux XIIIe et XIVe si\u00e8cles''.</ref> He was the son of [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John of Ibelin]] (aka John of Jaffa)<ref>{{citation | journal=[[The English Historical Review]]| title=The Ibelin Counts of Jaffa: A Previously Unknown Passage from the 'Lignages d'Outremer'|last=Edbury|jstor=567428 |date=July 1974|publisher=Oxford University Press| \npages = 604\u2013610 | volume=89| issue=352 | first1=P. | doi=10.1093/ehr/lxxxix.ccclii.604}}</ref><ref>Steven Runciman, ''History of the Crusades: Volume III'', p. 324\n</ref> and Maria of Barbaron.<ref>{{Citation|url= http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ARMENIA.htm|title=Armenia|\npublisher=Foundation for medieval genealogy|date=2008-07-28|accessdate=2008-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Nielen-Vandervoorde| first=Marie-Ad\u00e9la\u00efde |title=[[Lignages d'Outremer]]|\npublisher=Acad\u00e9mie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres|year= 2003|series=Documents relatifs \u00e0 l'histoire des Croisades|isbn=2-87754-141-X}}\n</ref> He was Count in name only.  His father, John of Jaffa, had died in 1266, after which the fragile truce with the Muslims collapsed, and Jaffa was captured by [[Baibars]] in 1268. John was probably succeeded by Guy's older brother James, who held the title of Count of Jaffa until his death in 1276, at which point the title passed to Guy.<ref>{{Citation|title=Warfare in the Latin East, 1192\u20131291|author=Marshall, Christopher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=142\u2013143|year=1992|isbn=0-521-39428-7}}</ref>\n\nIn 1299/1300, Guy was able to capture [[Jebail]] with a [[Republic of Genoa|Genoese]] fleet, but held it only briefly. He also met with the Mongol leader [[Kutlushah]] in 1301, in an unsuccessful attempt to coordinate a military attack against the Muslims.<ref>{{Citation|author=Richard, Jean|title=The Latin Kingdom of Jerusalem|publisher=North-Holland Publishing Company|year=1979|isbn=0-444-85262-X|pages=432\u2013433}}</ref> In 1302 he and his family were captured by pirates while staying at their ancestral fiefdom in [[Episkopi, Limassol|Episcopia]], [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{citation|title=Cyprus: Society and Culture 1191\u20131374|first=Angel|last= Nikolaou-Konnar\u0113|first2= Christopher David |last2=Schabel|publisher=BRILL|year= 2005|page=81|isbn=90-04-14767-5}}; {{citation|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k110089k|last=Amadi|first=Francesco|title= Chroniques d'Amadi et de Strambaldi |publisher=Ren\u00e9 de Mas)|year=1891|language=Italian|page=238}}; {{cite book |last1=Rogge |first1=Sabine |last2=Gr\u00fcnbart |first2=Michael |title=Medieval Cyprus: a Place of Cultural Encounter |date=2015 |publisher=Waxmann Verlag |isbn=9783830983606 |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=FiIFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA152 |page=152 |accessdate=7 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe died on February 14, 1304, and was buried in [[Nicosia]], Cyprus, in a pauper's grave in accordance with his vows. Guy must have been held in high regard on the island, judging from the turmoil following his death reported by the chronicler Amadi.<ref>{{Citation|journal=[[The English Historical Review]]|title=The Ibelin Counts of Jaffa|author=Edbury, Peter|date=July 1974|publisher=Oxford University Press| \npages=604\u2013610|volume=89|issue=352|doi=10.1093/ehr/lxxxix.ccclii.604}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k110089k|last=Amadi|first=Francesco|title= Chroniques d'Amadi et de Strambaldi (publi\u00e9es par M. Ren\u00e9 de Mas)|year=1891}}, p. 240: '' \"per rechiese per deviocion lui de esser sepulto con li poveri\" ''; '' \"di gran danno a l'isola de Cypro, imperoch\u00e8 molti scandali, travagli et inconvenienti acorseno, che se fosse stato lui vivo non sariano stati come ho ditto.\" ''</ref>\n\n==Family==\nGuy married twice. His second wife was Maria, Lady of Ascalon and Naumachia, daughter of [[Philip of Ibelin (died 1304)|Philip of Ibelin]] and Simone de Montbeliard.  Guy and Maria had five children:<ref>{{Citation|url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/JERUSALEM%20NOBILITY.htm#_Toc166845936|title=Jerusalem nobility: Count and Lords of Jaffa (Ibelin)|publisher=Foundation for medieval genealogy|date=2007-05-14|accessdate=2008-11-23}}</ref>\n* Philip (born before 1293, died 1315/1316 in [[Kyrenia]]), Count of Jaffa\n* John (died 1315/1316 in Kyrenia)\n* Maria (b. 1294, died before 1318), first wife of the man who later became [[Hugh IV of Cyprus]] in 1324\n* Hugh (b. 1295/1300, died before May 10, 1349), Count of Jaffa, and then Seneschal of Jerusalem.  Second husband of Isabella of Ibelin, widow of Infante don Fernando de Mallorca and daughter of Philip of Ibelin, Seneschal of Cyprus, and his second wife Maria of Giblet.\n* Balian (b. 1298/1300), married Joan of Montfort, daughter of [[Rupen of Montfort]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[Templar of Tyre]], [http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/basis/GuillaumeTyr5.html Online]\n\n[[Category:Counts of Jaffa and Ascalon]]\n[[Category:13th-century births]]\n[[Category:1304 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others of this name|Guy of Ibelin (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Ibelin\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| image_size        = 150px\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        = titular count of Jaffa and Ascalon\n| reign             = 1266 - 1304\n| predecessor       = [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John (jurist)]]\n| successor         = Philip (his son)\n| spouse            = Maria of Ibelin, Lady of Ascalon and Naumachia\n| issue             = Philip, Count of Jaffa<br>John<br>Maria, wife of [[Hugh IV of Cyprus]]<br>Hugh, Seneschal of Jerusalem<br>Balian\n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]\n| father            = [[John of Ibelin (jurist)|John (jurist)]]\n| mother            = Maria of Barbaron\n| birth_date        = 1250/1255\n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1304\n}}\n\n'''Guy of Ibelin''' (French: Guy d'Ibelin) (1250/1255 \u2013 1304), of the [[Ibelin family]], was [[County of Jaffa and Ascalon|Count of Jaffa and Ascalon]] during the latter part of the [[Crusades]].<ref>{{citation|first=W. H. |last=Rudt de Collenberg|title=Les Ibelin aux XIIIe et 